Hotel Booking Demand - Classification Modeling¶

Introduction:

This data set contains booking information from two different hotels, a resort hotel and a city hotel located in Portugal. The resort hotel is located in the region of Algarve and the city hotel is located in the city of Lisbon. The data includes information such as when the booking was made, the length of stay, the number of adults, children, and/or babies, the number of available parking spaces, customer type, whether the booking was cancelled, guest country of origin, average daily rate, etc. All of the bookings were due to arrive between July 1, 2015 and August 31, 2017. The data set can be obtained at: https://www.kaggle.com/jessemostipak/hotel-booking-demand#

The goal is to accurately predict whether or not a hotel booking was cancelled based on the booking information provided. Information/knowledge such as this could prove very useful for the hospitality industry for obvious reasons. The below analysis includes some preliminary data exploration, and ultimately culminates with the construction and comparison of several classification models. Multinomial Naive Bayes, KNN, SVM, & Random Forest models are explored, utilizing individual grid searches to optimize/tune model hyperparameters. Finally, all four models are compared using ROC curves.

The variables is_canceled and is_repeated_guest are really categorical in nature but are represented as numbers. The last column, reservation_status_date, is an ordinal attribute, but in most cases is identical to the arrival date. Reservation_status also more or less mirrors the variable is_cancelled, and will therefore be dropped.

Explore data:¶

Look at categorical variable class distributions:

cats = ['arrival_date_month', 'is_repeated_guest', 'distribution_channel', 'is_canceled', 'hotel', 'meal', 'country', 'market_segment', 'reserved_room_type', 'assigned_room_type', 'deposit_type', 'customer_type']

month_abv = {'January': 'Jan', 'February': 'Feb', 'March': 'Mar', 'April': 'Apr', 'June': 'Jun', 'July': 'Jul', 'August': 'Aug', 'September': 'Sept', 'October': 'Oct', 'November': 'Nov', 'December': 'Dec'}
data = data.replace(month_abv)

market_seg = {'Aviation': 'Air', 'Corporate': 'Corp', 'Direct': 'Dir', 'Undefined': 'Undef', 'Groups': 'Group', 'Offline TA/TO': 'Off TA/TO', 'Online TA': 'On TA', 'Complementary': 'Comp'}
data = data.replace(market_seg)

sns.set(style = 'darkgrid')
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 16))
ax.axis('off')
fig.tight_layout()
for idx, i in enumerate(cats):
    labels = list(data[i].value_counts().index)
    values = list(data[i].value_counts())
    fig.add_subplot(4,3,idx+1)
    plt.bar(labels, values)
    plt.xticks(labels)
    plt.title(i.upper())

From the above bar plots of the categorical variables, we can see that the three summer months of August, July, and May had the highest number of hotel bookings. We can see that most guests only had a breakfast (BB) meal type booked. The TA/TO distribution channel and market segment appears to be the most prevalent. Moreover, the most popular room type reserved (and assigned) was room A. Most guests did not provide a desposit and were labeled as transient (as opposed to contract or group) customer types. Furthermore, the classes of the target variable is_cancelled (to be used in the following classification modeling) do not appear to be too unbalanced.

The vast majority of hotel guests came from Portugal. This intuitively makes sense, as both of the hotels in this data set are located in Portugal. A large number of guests also came from Great Britain, France, Spain, and Germany (other European countries).

Look at the percentage of cancellations per month for each hotel type (city & resort) :

In [14]:
# resort hotel bookings and cancellations:
res_booked = data[(data['hotel'] == 'Resort Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['hotel'].count()
res_cancelled = data[(data['hotel'] == 'Resort Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['is_canceled'].sum()

res_cancelled_data = pd.DataFrame({'Hotel': 'Resort Hotel',
                                'Month': list(res_booked.index),
                                'Bookings': list(res_booked.values),
                                'Cancellations': list(res_cancelled.values)})

# city hotel bookings and cancellations:
city_booked = data[(data['hotel'] == 'City Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['hotel'].count()
city_cancelled = data[(data['hotel'] == 'City Hotel')].groupby('arrival_date_month')['is_canceled'].sum()

city_cancelled_data = pd.DataFrame({'Hotel': 'City Hotel',
                                'Month': list(city_booked.index),
                                'Bookings': list(city_booked.values),
                                'Cancellations': list(city_cancelled.values)})

# cancellation percentages:
full_cancelled_data = pd.concat([res_cancelled_data, city_cancelled_data], ignore_index=True)
full_cancelled_data['cancel_percent'] = full_cancelled_data['Cancellations'] / full_cancelled_data['Bookings'] * 100

# ordered months:
months_ordered = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 
          'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sept', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
full_cancelled_data['Month'] = pd.Categorical(full_cancelled_data['Month'], categories=months_ordered, ordered=True)

# plot:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.barplot(x = 'Month', y = 'cancel_percent', hue = 'Hotel',
            hue_order = ['City Hotel', 'Resort Hotel'], data = full_cancelled_data)
plt.title('Cancellation Percentages per Month', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Percent Cancelled', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(loc= 'upper right')
plt.show()

The percentage of hotel bookings cancelled per month appears to be consistently higher for city hotels than resort hotels across all months.

Perform Classification Modeling:¶

MULTINOMIAL NAIVE BAYES:

Perform classification using multinomial naive bayes and a grid search to optimize the parameters:

In [19]:
nb = MultinomialNB()
alphas = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4]
parameters = {'alpha': alphas, 'fit_prior' : [True, False]}      # grid search parameters
gs = GridSearchCV(nb, parameters, verbose=1, cv=5)
In [20]:
gs.fit(x_train, y_train)     # perform grid search on training data

Fitting 5 folds for each of 18 candidates, totalling 90 fits

GridSearchCV(cv=5, estimator=MultinomialNB(),
             param_grid={'alpha': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2,
                                   0.3, 0.4],
                         'fit_prior': [True, False]},
             verbose=1)

The optimal value of alpha is: 0.0001
The optimal value of fit_prior is: True

The best cross-validation accuracy on the training data was: 0.7503460067424925

Using the optimal parameters (alpha = .0001 and fit_prior = True), apply model to set aside test data:

In [22]:
nb = MultinomialNB(alpha=.0001, fit_prior=True)  # initialize classifier with smoothing parameter alpha = .0001  & allow it to learn prior class probabilities

nb.fit(x_train, y_train)                        # fit on training data

pred_test_target = nb.predict(x_test)           # predict classes of test set

print(classification_report(y_test, pred_test_target))  # print classification report

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

         0.0       0.72      0.99      0.83     15070
         1.0       0.97      0.33      0.49      8772

    accuracy                           0.75     23842
   macro avg       0.85      0.66      0.66     23842
weighted avg       0.81      0.75      0.71     23842

Although this multinomial naive bayes classifier is only correctly predicting whether a hotel booking was cancelled 75% of the time, it has a relatively high precision (97%) with respect to the cancelled class. That is, it is not incorrectly predicting that a hotel reservation was cancelled very often. This is important because in order for the hospitality industry to presumably make use of classification models such as this, it would be beneficial to err on the side of caution when attempting to determine whether hotel bookings will ultimately be cancelled (to prevent overbooking).

This knn classifier is correctly predicting whether a hotel booking was cancelled 83% of the time. This is an improvement from the prior multinomial naive bayes classifier in terms of overall accuracy. However, the precision (77%) with respect to the cancelled class is worse. This model misclassified more reservations as cancelled that were actually not cancelled.

    accuracy                           0.90     23842
   macro avg       0.90      0.88      0.89     23842
weighted avg       0.90      0.90      0.90     23842

This random forest classifier is accurately predicting whether a hotel booking was cancelled 90% of the time. This is a relatively high overall accuracy, which is better than the three prior models. The precision (89%) with respect to the cancelled class is better than the knn and svm classifiers, but still not as good as the first multinomial naive bayes classifier. The hospitality industry might want to adopt a model such as this over the first multinomial naive bayes classifier as part of their marketing strategy if pursuing a more aggressive approach. However, doing so would likely increase the risk of potential overbookings.

Compare all four models using ROC curves:¶

In [45]:
models = [
{
    'label': 'Multinomial NB',
    'model': MultinomialNB(alpha=.0001, fit_prior=True),
},
{
    'label': 'KNN',
    'model': neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5),
},
{
    'label': 'SVM',
    'model': SVC(gamma='scale', C=250, kernel='rbf', class_weight='balanced', probability=True),
},
{
    'label': 'Random Forest',
    'model': ensemble.RandomForestClassifier(criterion='gini', min_samples_split=2, n_estimators=100),
}
]
# iterate through models list:
for m in models:
    model = m['model']              # select the model
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)  # train the model
    y_pred = model.predict(x_test)      # predict the test data
# compute false postive rate, and true positive rate:
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1])
# calculate AUC to display on the plot:
    auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test))
# plot the computed values:
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='%s ROC (area = %0.2f)' % (m['label'], auc))
# settings for the plot: 
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'k--',label='No Skill')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (1-Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(loc='lower right')  # legend location
plt.show()                     # display

The above graph shows the performance for each of the four models (Multinomial Naive Bayes, KNN, SVM, & Random Forest) over a range of probability thresholds. The random forest classifier performed very well, with highest respective AUC (area under the curve). And although the multinomial naive bayes classifier has a relatively low AUC, as mentioned earlier this classifier displayed the highest precision with respect to the cancelled class.
